{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614398"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16361"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.17,0.29,0.08,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64871"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7179"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7197"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21525"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64871"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves has nuclei located at the pontomedullary junction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oculomotor nerve (CN III)","Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)","Facial nerve (CN VII)","Trigeminal nerve (CN V)","Vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve (CN VII)\u003C/strong\u003E has multiple nuclei distributed in the brainstem. While its motor nucleus is located in the pons, its parasympathetic nuclei (superior salivatory nucleus and lacrimal nucleus) are found at the pontomedullary junction. These nuclei are responsible for innervating the submandibular, sublingual, and lacrimal glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve (CN III)\u003C/strong\u003E nuclei are located in the midbrain at the level of the superior colliculus. These include the main motor nucleus and the Edinger-Westphal nucleus for parasympathetic function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)\u003C/strong\u003E has its nuclei in the medulla oblongata, including the nucleus ambiguus (motor), inferior salivatory nucleus (parasympathetic), and solitary nucleus (sensory).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve (CN V)\u003C/strong\u003E has its main sensory nucleus extending throughout the brainstem, but its motor nucleus is located in the upper pons, not at the pontomedullary junction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII)\u003C/strong\u003E has its nuclei (vestibular and cochlear) located in the pons, not at the pontomedullary junction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the location of cranial nerve nuclei is crucial for localising lesions in the brainstem. The arrangement of these nuclei follows a logical pattern that helps in clinical diagnosis of various neurological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The facial nerve (CN VII) has its motor nucleus in the pons and its parasympathetic nuclei at the pontomedullary junction.","The superior salivatory nucleus and lacrimal nucleus of CN VII are located at the pontomedullary junction.","Understanding cranial nerve nuclei locations helps localise brainstem lesions."],"references":["Sanders RD. The Trigeminal (V) and Facial (VII) Cranial Nerves: Head and Face Sensation and Movement. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Jan;7(1):13-6. PMID: 20386632; PMCID: PMC2848459.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50305"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T21:09:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T21:09:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64871"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"update